</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[138,267,137,161]" box="[138,267,137,161]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1421">
<emphasis box="[138,267,137,161]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1421">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[138,1185,185,307]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1421">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chen &amp; Kottelat" authorityYear="2005" box="[138,380,185,209]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Rhinogobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="1421" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="variolatus">
<emphasis box="[138,380,185,209]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1421">Rhinogobius variolatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is presently known only from the Ba Che drainage and an unnamed creek north of Cam Pha (
<figureCitation box="[426,522,218,242]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[125,185,1638,1657]" captionTargetBox="[173,1124,1007,1600]" captionTargetId="figure-254@3.[170,1127,1004,1601]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Distribution of Rhinogobius boa (white triangles), R. sulcatus (diamond), R. variolatus (squares), and R. virgigena (black triangle) in north-eastern Vietnam. A, Mong Cai; B, Tien Yen; C, Ba Che; D, Mong Duong." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5214686" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5214686/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="1421">Figure 1</figureCitation>
). It was collected in a small, shallow coastal stream with a gravel to boulder substratum, and from the Ba Che river, which in the rainy season was flowing swift, turbid water over large boulders.
</paragraph>
